Today I want to show you how we will make things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be able to self-assemble, self-replicate and self-repair.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current state of manufacturing and then compare it to some natural systems.
So in current manufacturing, we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, half a million to a million parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, two and a half million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that fold up in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we can build, more complex than anything we can build.
They are more energy efficient.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves to maintain longevity.
There's something super interesting about natural systems.
If we can translate that into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the intricacies of what we're going to build -- our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences - basically the DNA of how our architecture works.
Then we need the programmable part that can take this sequence and use it to fold or reshape.
We need some energy to activate so that these parts of us can be folded in accordance with the program.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to ensure that we successfully build what we want.
So I'm going to show you some of the projects that my colleagues and I are working on to realize this self-assembled future.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are all large-scale reconfigurable robots -- 8-foot, 12-foot-long proteins.
They are embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into, decode into a series of angles -- minus 120 degrees, minus 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, minus 120 degrees, -- things like that; a series of angles, or turns, and you can wire that order through.
Each unit gets its own message - say minus 120. It rotates, checks to see if it's in place and passes the sequence to its neighbors.
There are many brilliant scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, it took thousands of dollars for a lot of people to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really scale it up? Can we really embed robots in every part?
The next question is to look at passiveness, or passively trying to make reorganization programmable.
But it goes a step further, it tries to do the actual calculation.
Basically embedding the fundamental building blocks of most computing, digital logic gates, goes directly into the various parts.
This is a NAND gate.
There is one tetrahedron on each gate to be used for the calculation, and there are two input tetrahedra.
One of them is input from the user, like you're building bricks.
The other is the input of a brick that was placed before coming.
Then it gives the output in 3D space.
This means that users stack bricks the way they want.
It calculates based on what was done before and your instructions.
Now it starts to move in 3D space - up or down.
Looking at the left, the input of [1,1] is equal to 0 output, which means down.
On the right, the input of [0,0] is 1 output, indicating upwards.
So what this really means is that our structure now contains the blueprints that we want to build.
So the information about what you want to build is all embedded in it.
This means we have some form of self-replication.
For this case, I call it self-directed replication, because your structure contains the exact blueprint.
If you encounter an error, you can replace a section.
All the local info is embedded in it telling you how to fix it.
So you have something you can climb, read it and output one by one.
It is directly embedded; no external command input.
