Password - we call it an encryption key.
You can think of it like a password.
The call that told James the password.
We call it key passing.
This ensures that we can deliver the key securely to the designated location.
And a lock to encrypt and decrypt files.
We call it an encryption algorithm.
With the secret key, it converts the contents of the file into random numbers.
A good algorithm can do this, it is very difficult to crack the password without the secret key.
The importance of algorithms is that if someone gets a briefcase, opens it, and doesn't have the secret key, and doesn't know the encryption algorithm, they can't read the contents of the document.
All you get is some random numbers.
Most security systems rely on secure key delivery to get the keys to the right place.
However, rapidly increasing computing power jeopardizes many of the key transfer methods we currently use.
As an example, we have a very widely used system - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it took about 4 quadrillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
And in 1994, just 17 years later, the code was cracked.
As computers become more powerful, we need longer passwords.
Now we often use 2048 or 4096-bit passwords.
As you can see, the battle is going on between the encryptors and the decrypters, both trying to win the other.
In the next 10 to 15 years, the advent of quantum computers will make it faster to crack the complex mathematical algorithms that underlie the encryption systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our safe castle into a knock-down house of cards.
We will try to protect our castle.
In recent years, many research institutions have emerged to study how to use quantum effects to enhance encryption.
People have made some exciting breakthroughs.
Remember the 3 key points of encryption: high quality keys, secure key transfer and strong algorithms.
However, advances in science and engineering have compromised two of these priorities.
First and foremost is the secret key.
Random numbers are the basis of the secret key.
But today, they are no longer truly random.
At present, we generate the secret key, which is generated by software according to the frequency of random numbers, which we call pseudo-random numbers.
Numbers generated by programs or mathematical methods will always have some, perhaps not so obvious rules in them.
The less random these numbers are, or in terminology, the lower the moisture they contain, the more predictable they are.
Recently, some casinos have been attacked in a creative way.
